      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "It was while in the Galapagos, observing small birds called finches, that Darwin started forming his theory of evolution. But today the animals of the Galapagos face the same pressures as animals",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.955895",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"BI\", \"LED\", \"ES\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "46bbd7db-fd5d-466f-a481-3ac06893b7a7",
      "chunk_index": 2,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "across the world because of the effects of man-made climate change. Warming sea waters and more frequent extreme weather events are affecting animals as much as humans. So in this programme we'll be asking can animals evolve to deal with climate change? But first, I have a question for you, Sam, and it's about Charles Darwin's trip to the Galapagos.",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.958379",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"軟實力\", \"ES\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "ddcb4cd4-2e8a-42c4-beea-50a43ddf2a58",
      "chunk_index": 3,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "Maybe it was B, HMS Victory? Are you sure? No. OK. Well, I'll reveal the correct answer later in the programme. Now it may have been the Galapagos finches that started Charles Darwin thinking about how",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.960680",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"ES\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "e59f5c7a-163d-42e4-8aa6-934f4f01c6a0",
      "chunk_index": 4,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "animals adapt to their environment, but as naturalist Kyoko Gotunda explained to BBC World Service programme The Climate Question, Darwin's first impression of the small birds wasn't very good.",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.963009",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"BI\", \"XP\", \"ES\", \"AI\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "0d1d8942-32fd-44c8-96b4-a55fa24fcfcb",
      "chunk_index": 5,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "In contrast to more colourful birds like Galapagos parrots, the finches, Darwin observed, were drab, dull and boring looking with little colour.",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.965250",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"BI\", \"ES\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "737372c0-8335-4b02-9dd7-c81e7e07d825",
      "chunk_index": 6,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "So if animals can evolve to survive their environment, can they also evolve to cope with the impact humans are having on the climate?",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.967458",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "24797df8-8f09-4289-9b4f-4bb7a50629ab",
      "chunk_index": 7,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "American conservationist Thor Hansen records and measures Anoli lizards in the Caribbean. He wants to see how the effects of man-made climate change, in this case hurricanes, is affecting the lizards. Listen to what Thor found out as he speaks with presenters of BBC World Services",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.969858",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"ES\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "98fefcf2-0360-4066-b9f1-1b0ffdc1b85e",
      "chunk_index": 8,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "But what you can see is that large toe pads and strong front legs give some lizards a tighter grip. So the survivors were those lizards with those characteristics and they passed those traits along to their offspring.",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.972144",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"AI\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "8ca16f50-3c79-479a-8661-dacdf55d4209",
      "chunk_index": 9,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "It's this trait, a genetically determined characteristic, that allows the lizards to survive and is passed on to their babies. Thor checked other areas of the Caribbean where hurricanes were frequent and found the same traits in lizards there. Proof of evolution in action. But whereas we often think of evolution happening over hundreds,",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.974588",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"BI\", \"軟實力\", \"ES\", \"AI\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "63d3a965-dae7-445a-b75e-9e16e5d26c18",
      "chunk_index": 10,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "thousands of years, the changes in the Caribbean lizards happened in around 40 years. Something that would have surprised Charles Darwin. Rich, remind me of your question, Rob. Ah yes, I asked you the name of the ship Darwin sailed around the world in. Darwin's ship was called the HMS Beagle and appropriately enough it was named after an animal. A beagle is a type of dog. OK, let's recap the vocabulary from this programme about evolution.",
      "embedding": [],
      "language": "zh",
      "created_at": "2025-07-10T14:45:12.977187",
      "source_model": "text-embedding-ada-002",
      "tags": "[\"LED\", \"ES\", \"AI\"]"
    },
    {
      "chunk_id": "abd6f941-ffe7-4577-96e8-752e99a0cc17",
      "chunk_index": 11,
      "episode_id": "6865015b66c1a4e8d1176643",
      "podcast_id": "1304",
      "podcast_name": "",
      "author": "",
      "category": "",
      "episode_title": "Climate change and evolution",
      "duration": "",
      "published_date": "",
      "apple_rating": 0,
      "chunk_text": "The way living things adapt to their environment and pass these adaptations on to their children. Flora and fauna is another way of saying the plants and animals of a place. Drab means dull and colourless in appearance. A bird's beak is the hard pointed part of its mouth. To cling on means to hold on very tightly. And finally, a trait is a genetically determined characteristic.",
      "embedding": [],
